## 7. Conclusions and Policy Implications

Terrorism poses a multifaceted threat to global trade by increasing uncertainty, disrupting supply chains, raising costs, and deterring investment. Its impact is particularly severe in developing countries and high-skilled manufacturing sectors. While post-9/11 security measures have improved supply chain safety, they have also introduced inefficiencies and costs.

Trade law and international agreements currently constrain proactive supply chain regulation, limiting countries’ ability to mitigate terrorism-related risks before crises occur. Reforming trade rules to allow greater flexibility for preventative measures and encouraging supply chain diversification is essential for enhancing global trade resilience.

Governments, businesses, and international organizations must collaborate to balance security and efficiency, invest in data-driven supply chain management, and address the root causes of terrorism to safeguard the future of global trade.

